arlos Williams’s Paterson and John Montague’s The Rough Field -- tPoetry to Music: Gil Scott-Heron’s Intermedial Performance Aesthetics -- tThe Intermedial Poetry of Rap: Words, Sounds, and Music Videos -- tGrime Poetry: Black British Rap Lyric(s) in the Twenty-First Century -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQuestions of genres as well as their possible definitions, taxonomies, and functions have been discussed since antiquity. Even though categories of genre today are far from being fixed, they have for decades been upheld without question. The goal of this volume is to problematize traditional definitions of poetic genres and to situate them in a broader socio-cultural, historical, and theoretical context. The contributions encompass numerous methodological approaches (including hermeneutics, poststructuralism, reception theory, cultural studies, gender studies), periods (Romanticism, Modernism, Postmodernism), genres (elegy, sonnet, visual poetry, performance poetry, hip hop) as well as languages and national literatures. From this interdisciplinary and multi-methodological perspective, genres, periods, languages, and literatures are put into fruitful dialogue, new perspectives are discovered, and suggestions for further research are provided.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aLiterary form. 0aPoetics. 0aPoetryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aGenre.  aInterdisciplinary.  aLiterary Studies.  aPoetry.1 aBalestrini, Nassim Winnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBundschuh, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmig, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb